- Cumulative size change refers to the total increase or decrease in size of a segment over multiple versions of an executable file; 
- Executable files are computer files that contain a set of instructions that a computer can directly execute, usually to run an application; 
- Segments within an executable file are sections of the file that contain specific types of data, such as code (.text) or data that is initialized (.data); 
- API (Application Programming Interface) calls relate to how different applications interact with each other, and in this context, are considered in relation to their impact on the executable file's segments.
